Prior to moving on to the fully specified model, it is advisable to first examine the simple associations between the outcome and each individual predictor. Doing so can help avoid surprises in the final model. For example, if there is no simple relationship apparent in the data, we shouldnât be taken aback when that predictor is not significant in the model.

Graphs are again helpful. When the outcome is categorical and the predictor is also categorical, a grouped bar graph is informative. The following is the graph of survival and sex.

titanic %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Sex, 
             y = ..prop.., 
             group = survived_factor,
             fill = survived_factor)) + 
  geom_bar( position = 'dodge') +

Having carefully reviewed the data, we can now move to estimating the model.

Fitting the Model

To fit a logistic regression in R, we will use the glm function, which stands for Generalized Linear Model. Within this function, write the dependent variable, followed by ~, and then the independent variables separated by +âs. When the family is specified as binomial, R defaults to fitting a logistic regression model. Note that we are also treating Pclass as a numeric variable here. Note that 0 = drowned and 1 = survived.

Exercise 9: Running the model

Fill in the blanks below to put the appropriate DV: survived_factor, IVs: Sex + Pclass + Age, and family = binomial

#creating the logistic regression model called mod_log
mod_log <-  titanic %>% 
  glm(formula = survived_factor ~ Sex + Pclass + Age, family = binomial)

Below, inside of tidy() add: exponentiate = T, conf.int = T

#exponentiation of the model and outputting a table
mod_log %>%
  tidy(exponentiate = T, conf.int = T) %>%
  mutate_if(is.numeric, ~ round(.,3)) %>%
  kable(align = c("l", rep("c", 6)))
term estimate std.error statistic p.value conf.low conf.high
(Intercept) 156.962 0.502 10.069 0 60.417 433.656
Sexmale 0.080 0.207 -12.168 0 0.053 0.120
Pclass 0.276 0.139 -9.253 0 0.208 0.360
Age 0.964 0.008 -4.841 0 0.949 0.978

The broom package contains useful functions, like tidy(), for viewing the output from common models. The conf.int = T argument requests confidence intervals.

Because Sex is a factor variable, R will automatically create dummy variables for us. Pclass is an ordered categorical variable, we opt here to treat its effect as linear. The last variable is age. We find that Sex, age, and PClass have significant effects.

We look at our results in terms of odds ratios by setting exponentiate = T in the tidy() function.

This will produce a table where:

  • estimate is the odds ratio
  • std.error is the standard error of the odds ratio
  • statistic is the z-statistic
  • p.value is the significance
  • conf.low is the lower level of the 95% confidence interval for the odds ratios
  • conf.high is the upper level of the 95% confidence interval for the odds ratios

Interpretation of Odds Ratios

An odds ratio less than one means that an increase in x leads to a decrease in the odds that y=1.

An odds ratio greater than one means that an increase in x leads to an increase in the odds that y=1.

Exercise 10: Interpret the Significant Odds Ratios from the table above.

ANSWER:

Males, compared to females, have a decreased odd of .08 of surviving.

As ticket class increases, passengers have an decreased off of surviving by .28.

As Age increases, passengers have a decreased odd of .96 of surviving.

In general, the percent change in the odds given a one-unit change in the predictor can be determined as:

% Change in Odds=100(OR-1)

For example, the odds of surviving are 100(.08-1) = -92% lower for males compared to females.

Bootstrapping the Mean IMDB Rating

We will be using data from The Office.

Specifically, we will use theoffice data from the schrute package to estimate mean IMDB scores for episodes of The Office.

First, letâs load our packages.

library(tidyverse)
library(tidymodels)
library(schrute)
library(lubridate)
library(psych)

There are many things we can bootstrap but the goal for this first exercise will be to bootstrap the mean imdb_rating.

Below are the steps for bootstrapping:

  1. Take a bootstrap sample - a random sample taken with replacement from the original sample, of the same size as the original sample

  2. Calculate the bootstrap statistic - a statistic such as mean, median, proportion, slope, etc. computed on the bootstrap samples

  3. Repeat steps (1) and (2) many times to create a bootstrap distribution - a distribution of bootstrap statistics

  4. Calculate the bounds of the XX% confidence interval as the middle XX% of the bootstrap distribution

Exercise 1

Fill in the blanks below to successfully create office_boot. You will need to take the theoffice dataset, specify imdb_rating as the response, generate 100 samples, and calculate the mean.

set.seed(8888)
# save resulting bootstrap distribution
office_boot <- theoffice %>%
  # specify the variable of interest
  specify(response = imdb_rating) %>% 
  # generate 50 bootstrap samples
  generate(reps = 50, type = "bootstrap") %>% 
  # calculate the mean of each bootstrap sample
  calculate(stat = "mean")

Exercise 2

How many observations are there in office_boot? What does each observation represent?

ANSWER: Each observation represents a bootstrapped mean

Bootstrapping a Slope

For the final set of exercises, we will again be using data from The Office.

This time, we are going to bootstrap a slope. Specifically, we will use imdb_rating as the DV and season as the IV.

Exercise 7

Fill in the blanks below to successfully create office_boot_slope. You will need to take the theoffice dataset, specify imdb_rating as the response (DV), specify season (IV) as the explanatory variable, generate 50 samples, and calculate the slope.

set.seed(8888)
# save resulting bootstrap distribution
office_boot_slope <- theoffice %>%
  # specify the variable of interest
  specify(response = imdb_rating,
          explanatory = season) %>% 
  # generate 50 bootstrap samples
  generate(reps = 50, type = "bootstrap") %>% 
  # calculate the mean of each bootstrap sample
  calculate(stat = "slope")

How many observations are there in office_boot? What does each observation represent?

ANSWER: Each observation represents a bootstrapped slope
